e with the words “MOUNT EVEREST” partly visible, and behind it is a framed mountain picture. The box is dark blue with large white and yellow lettering: “Alka-Seltzer Plus Cold Medicine.” A red label reads “Fast Relief,” and a graphic of a fizzing tablet appears near the lower right of the front panel. Smaller text is present but not fully legible. The product remains centered and well lit as the box is shown from slightly different angles, making the brand name and medicine type clear. A small white instruction, “Use only as directed,” appears at the bottom of the screen while the box is still displayed. The snowy expedition images return. A mountaineer, bundled in a muted purple or brown parka with hood up, climbs a bright white slope. The person leans forward under a heavy black pack, planting a pole into the snow. A rope trails across the snow behind or beside them, suggesting a roped climb. Close views show black mountaineering boots fitted with crampons stepping into the snow, the metal points gripping the surface as each foot presses down. The climber’s lower legs are dark, speckled with snow, and the movement is slow and deliberate. In profile, the same or another climber is shown wearing a purple hood, a cap or helmet cover, round dark goggles, red and white mittens, and a large backpack. A beard is visible below the goggles, and the climber grips a pole while facing the vast pale landscape. The posture is upright but braced, as if pausing on the slope. Walt appears again in the warm interview room, his face close to the screen. He looks downward, then raises his gaze toward the viewer, continuing to speak with a composed, matter-of-fact expression. Back on the mountain, two climbers in bulky parkas embrace on a snowy ridge or high camp area. One wears a bright orange-red parka with a hood and has a rope or harness around the waist; the other is darker-clad and partly hidden by the hug. Snowy cliffs and slopes rise behind them. Their arms wrap tightly aroun